\begin_layout Standard
The compressible Navier-Stokes equations has the conservative form: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:NS}
    \frac{\partial \U}{\partial t} +
    (\F - \F_v) \cdot \mathbf\nabla = 0
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\U$
\end_inset

 is vector of conservative quantities and 
\begin_inset Formula $\F=[\F_1,\F_2,\F_3]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\F_v=[\F_{v,1},\F_{v,2},\F_{v,3}]$
\end_inset

 are inviscid and viscous tensors of their flux. In cartesian coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x_k, k=1,2,3$
\end_inset

, the components are 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \U = \begin{bmatrix}
        \rho \\ \rho u_1 \\ \rho u_2 \\ \rho u_3 \\ E
    \end{bmatrix},\ \
    \F_j = \begin{bmatrix}
        \rho u_j                   \\
        \rho u_1u_j + p\delta_{1j} \\
        \rho u_2u_j + p\delta_{2j} \\
        \rho u_3u_j + p\delta_{3j} \\
        (E+p)u_j                   \\
    \end{bmatrix},\ \
    \F_{v,j} = \begin{bmatrix}
        0                                \\
        \tau_{1j}                        \\
        \tau_{2j}                        \\
        \tau_{3j}                        \\
        \sum_{k=1}^3{u_k\tau_{kj}} - K_j \\
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is density, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_i, i=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 are velocity components, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is pressure, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is total energy per unit volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{ij}, i,j=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 are viscous stress tensor components and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_i, i=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 are heat flux components. 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is Kronecker delta. With ideal gas equation of state, Newtonian viscosity and Fourier heat conduction, additional relations 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        E         & = \frac{p}{\gamma -1 } + \frac{1}{2}\rho\sum_{k=1}^{3}(u_ku_k)  \\
        p         & =\rho R_g T                                                     \\
        \tau_{ij} & =
        \mu\left(\frac{\partial u_i}{\partial x_j} + \frac{\partial u_j}{\partial x_i}\right)
        -
        \frac{2}{3}\mu \delta_{ij}\sum_{k=1}^{3}{\frac{\partial u_k}{\partial x_k}} \\
        K_i       & = - \kappa \frac{\partial T}{\partial x_i}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

are used to close the equations with 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 being temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 being specific heat ratio, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_g$
\end_inset

 being gas constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 being dynamic viscosity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 being thermal conductivity. Specific heat ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is fixed to 
\begin_inset Formula $1.4$
\end_inset

 in this paper. The current paper only considers using simple gas property with 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa = \mu c_p / Pr$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\mu_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 being a constant, while 
\begin_inset Formula $c_p$
\end_inset

 is special heat capacity at constant pressure and Prandtl number 
\begin_inset Formula $Pr$
\end_inset

 is fixed to 0.71 in this paper. When 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\F_v=0$
\end_inset

 and equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 becomes Euler equation. The equations discussed above are in 3D form, and assuming constant distribution of values over 
\begin_inset Formula $x_3$
\end_inset

 yields the 2D version of NS and Euler equations.
\end_layout

