\end_layout

\end_inset

 can also be considered as a scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:FVRecScalar}
    u_i(\x) = \overline{u}_i + \sum_{l=1}^{\mathrm{NDOF}(k)}{u_i^l\varphi_{i,l}(\x) }
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_i(\x)$
\end_inset

 is one of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\x), \rho u_1(\x)\dots$
\end_inset

 and should not be confused with the velocity components 
\begin_inset Formula $u_1, u_2, u_3$
\end_inset

 in the context of reconstruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{NDOF}(k)$
\end_inset

 polynomial bases for reconstruction on each cell. The current paper uses zero-mean Taylor basis for reconstruction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "wang2017compact_VR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. Given a specific reconstruction method, the reconstruction coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\U_i^l$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $u_i^l$
\end_inset

 for each scalar) can be determined using the distribution of mean value 
\begin_inset Formula $\UM_i, i=1,2...N_{cell}$
\end_inset

 and boundary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the piecewise polynomial approximation, the PDEs 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can therefore become ODEs with cell averaging applied 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:FVInt}
    \frac{\dd\UM_i}{\dd t}
    +\sum_{j\in S_i, j\neq i}{\left(
        \int_{f_{i,j}}{
            [\Fn(\U_i,\U_j) - \Fn_v(\U_i,\U_j, \nabla \U_i, \nabla \U_j)] \cdot \n  \dd A
        }\right)
    }
    = 0
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fn(\U_i,\U_j)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fn_v(\U_i,\U_j, \nabla \U_i, \nabla \U_j)$
\end_inset

 are approximations of exact fluxes on the cell interfaces, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i,j}=\OO_i \cap \OO_j$
\end_inset

 is the interface between 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 cells. Set 
\begin_inset Formula $S_i$
\end_inset

 denotes the compact stencil of cell 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

. The piecewise polynomial approximation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:FVRec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 does not guarantee a continuous distribution on interfaces, thus the numerical fluxes 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fn(\U_i,\U_j)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fn_v(\U_i,\U_j, \nabla \U_i, \nabla \U_j)$
\end_inset

 are functions of the approximate field on both sides. Inviscid numerical flux 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fn(\U_i,\U_j)$
\end_inset

 is typically an approximate Riemann solver which will be specified for each numerical test in the paper. Numerical viscous flux 
\begin_inset Formula $\Fn_v(\U_i,\U_j, \nabla \U_i, \nabla \U_j)$
\end_inset

 in this paper follows the practice of Wang 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "wang2017compact_VR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. The integration of flux terms on the cell interfaces are conducted using numerical quadrature rules with enough algebraic precision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the spacial derivatives are approximated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:FVInt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, it is referred to as the semi-discretized form of finite volume method. The inviscid term has a truncation error of 
\begin_inset Formula $O(h^{k+1})$
\end_inset

 for smooth problems, with 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 being the size of mesh. As the approximate fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\U_i$
\end_inset

 are functions of average values 
\begin_inset Formula $\UM_i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:FVInt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be rearranged into the assembled form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:FVODE}
    \frac{d\uu}{dt} = \R(t, \uu)
\end{equation}
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \uu = \begin{bmatrix}
        \UM_1 \\
        \dots \\
        \UM_{N_{cell}}
    \end{bmatrix},\ \
    \R = \begin{bmatrix}
        -\sum_{j\in S_1, j\neq 1}{\left(
            \int_{f_{1,j}}{
                [\Fn - \Fn_v] \cdot \n  dA
            }\right)
        }     \\
        \dots \\
        -\sum_{j\in S_{N_{cell}}, j\neq N_{cell}}{\left(
            \int_{f_{N_{cell},j}}{
                [\Fn - \Fn_v] \cdot \n  dA
            }\right)
        }
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

The arguments in the numerical fluxes are omitted. The right-hand-side vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 is also a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 because boundary conditions or additional source terms could depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 generally speaking.
\end_layout

