, a reconstruction method needs to be specified. Traditional 2nd order FV methods for unstructured grid needs only to reconstruct a 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 polynomial, namely linear distribution on each cell. The variational reconstruction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "wang2017compact_VR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a compact high-order reconstruction scheme, which features high-order accuracy achieved on a compact stencil. The current section will explain the variational reconstruction and specify relevant details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current paper uses local zero-mean Taylor basis, similar to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "wang2017compact_VR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. Taking 2 dimensional polynomials as an example: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \varphi_{i,l} & =
        \left(\frac{x - x_{c,i}}{\inc x_i}\right)^{p_l}
        \left(\frac{y - y_{c,i}}{\inc y_i}\right)^{q_l}
        -
        \overline{
            \left(\frac{x - x_{c,i}}{\inc x_i}\right)^{p_l}
            \left(\frac{y - y_{c,i}}{\inc y_i}\right)^{q_l}
        }
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $[x_{c,j},y_{c,j}]\trans = \x_{c,j}$
\end_inset

 are barycenters of cell 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc x_i,\inc y_i$
\end_inset

 are the cell's length scale, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_l,q_l$
\end_inset

 are powers of the bases. If 2-D 
\begin_inset Formula $k=3$
\end_inset

 basis is used, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_l=[1,0,2,1,0,3,2,1,0]_l$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_l=[0,1,0,1,2,0,1,2,3]_l$
\end_inset

. The mean value term makes the basis zero-mean, which is calculated with: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \overline{
        \left(\frac{x - x_{c,i}}{\inc x_i}\right)^{p_l}
        \left(\frac{y - y_{c,i}}{\inc y_i}\right)^{q_l}
    }
    =
    \frac{1}{\overline{\OO}_j}\int_{\OO_j}{
        \left(\frac{x - x_{c,i}}{\inc x_i}\right)^{p_l}
        \left(\frac{y - y_{c,i}}{\inc y_i}\right)^{q_l}
    }\dd \Omega
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The length scales are chosen to be the largest distance of nodes from the barycenter, which has the from 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \inc x_j = \inc y_j = \max_k(\|\x_{j,k} - \x_{c,j}\|_2)
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\x_{j,k}$
\end_inset

 are coordinates of nodes belonging to cell 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

. In this way the base functions are scaled to be isotropic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variational reconstruction defines the solution of reconstruction coefficients to be the minimum point of a globally defined functional 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    I = \sum{I_f}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_f$
\end_inset

 are interface jump integrations (IJI) defined on each cell interface 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

. Hereafter, we use 
\begin_inset Formula $f=f_{ij}$
\end_inset

 to denote the interface of cell 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 by default. Using 2-D as an example, the current paper uses IJI in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    I_f = \omega_f^G\int_{\OO_i \cap \OO_j}{
        \sum_{p+q=0}^{p + q\leq k}\left[
            \omega_f^D(p,q)
            \left(
            \partialderivative{^{p+q}u_i(x,y)}{x^p\partial y^q}
            -
            \partialderivative{^{p+q}u_j(x,y)}{x^p\partial y^q}
            \right)
            \right]^2
        \dd f
    }
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_f^G$
\end_inset

 is geometric weight and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_f^D$
\end_inset

 is derivative weight. The IJI represents facial discontinuities of reconstruction polynomials using function values and their various partial derivatives on the interface. For 2-D simulation and 3rd degree (4th order) reconstruction, the current paper uses 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \omega_f^D(0,0) & = 1\times \omega_D(0)                                                                                    \\
        \omega_f^D(1,0) & = \omega_f^D(0,1) = 1\times \omega_D(1)                                                                  \\
        \omega_f^D(2,0) & = \omega_f^D(0,2) = 1\times \omega_D(2),\ \omega_f^D(1,1) = \sqrt{2}\times \omega_D(2)                   \\
        \omega_f^D(3,0) & = \omega_f^D(0,3) = 1\times \omega_D(3),\ \omega_f^D(1,2) = \omega_f^D(2,1) = \sqrt{3}\times \omega_D(3) \\
    \end{aligned}
    \label{eq:wdRotRatio}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \omega_D(0) = 1, \omega_D(1) = 0.5925, \omega_D(2) = \omega_D(3) = 0.2117
    \label{eq:wdHQMOPT}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

as the derivative weight. This form of derivative weight in 
