\begin_layout Subsection
General Construction of DITR Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the first order ODE equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:FVODE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 arising from high-order finite volume method with 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu\in \mathbb{R}^N$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation*}
    \frac{\dd \uu}{\dd t} = \R(t, \uu)
\end{equation*}
\end_inset

which can be considered a more general first order ODE with 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu$
\end_inset

 being a general vector. For example, in finite difference, 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu$
\end_inset

 represents the vector of grid point values. A direct integration of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:FVODE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 leads to a time-marching relation 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \uu^{n+1} = \uu^{n} + \int_{t^n}^{t^{n+1}}{
    \R(t, \uu) \dd t
    }
    \label{eq:DI}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to acquire the integration result in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, a numeric quadrature rule in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[t^n, t^{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 is used. For example, the current paper uses three point polynomial quadrature rule 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:Quad3}
    \begin{aligned}
        \frac{\uu^{n+1} - \uu^{n}}{\inc t^n} = & \frac{1}{\inc t^n}
        \int_{t^n}^{t^{n+1}}{
        \R(t, \uu) \dd t
        }                                                           \\ \approx &
        b_1\R(t^n, \uu(t^n))
        +
        b_2\R(t^{n+c_2}, \uu(t^{n+c_2}))
        +
        b_3\R(t^{n+1}, \uu(t^{n+1}))
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n+c_2} = t^{n} + c_2 (t^{n+1} - t^n)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc t^n=t^{n+1} - t^n$
\end_inset

 is the time step size. The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

 represents the relative place of the second abscissa in the quadrature rule, where the first and third fixed at 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n + 1}$
\end_inset

. Using quadratic polynomial interpolation, the weights of the quadrature rule will be: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        b_1 & = \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{6{c_2}}     \\
        b_2 & = \frac{1}{6{c_2}(1-{c_2})}          \\
        b_3 & = \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{6(1-{c_2})} \\
    \end{aligned}
    \label{eq:integ0}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

The quadrature rule defined with equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:integ0"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has algebraic precision of degree 2. When 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2=1/2$
\end_inset

, the quadrature rule has algebraic precision of degree 3 and becomes the three point Gauss-Lobatto rule. The numeric integration process used in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is referred to as a direct integration process because it is directly derived from the ODE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The precise value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu(t)$
\end_inset

 at each 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[t^n, t^{n+1}]$
\end_inset

 is unknown, thus an approximation is required for numeric calculation. The current paper proposes to use conditions at time steps only, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $t \in \{t^{n+1}, t^n, t^{n-1}\dots\}$
\end_inset

, in acquiring the polynomial reconstruction. Since the step values 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^n, \uu^{n-1}\dots$
\end_inset

 and their temporal derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^n, \R^{n-1}\dots$
\end_inset

 are known, the addition of the unknown latest step 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+1}, \R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 makes the method implicit. The current paper has only considered using a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu(t), \R(t, \uu(t))$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $t \in \{t^{n+1}, t^n, t^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 as polynomial conditions. Generally, the polynomial interpolation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu(t)$
\end_inset

 could be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \label{eq:TR}
        \uu(t) & \approx
        A^n_0(t)\uu^{n - 1} +
        A^n_1(t)\uu^{n} +
        A^n_2(t)\uu^{n + 1}
        \\ & +
        \inc t^n D^n_0(t)\R^{n - 1} +
        \inc t^n D^n_1(t)\R^{n} +
        \inc t^n D^n_2(t)\R^{n + 1}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A^n_i(t), D^n_i(t), i=0,1,2$
\end_inset

 are polynomial base functions. Due to the precision of quadrature rule, the polynomial reconstruction is only expected to reach 3rd order constructing a 4th order accurate scheme. Consequently, at most 4 of the 6 conditions would be used at the same time. The polynomial interpolation in the direction of time in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TR"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is referred to as temporal reconstruction, for a continuous distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu$
\end_inset

 is reconstructed with point values, similar to the finite volume reconstruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining the direct integration in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and a temporal reconstruction in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TR"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, a Direct Integration with Temporal Reconstruction (DITR) method is determined. The current paper sticks to the same formula of direct integration in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, while experimenting on different forms of temporal reconstruction in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TR"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the quadrature rule in direct integration is replaced with midpoint rule, while the temporal reconstruction uses linear reconstruction, the implicit midpoint method for ODE can be derived, which is 2nd order accurate. A high order accurate DITR method could only be obtained with a high order accurate quadrature rule. For simplicity, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 only takes one interpolated node besides 
\begin_inset Formula $t^n, t^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, and has an accuracy of 3rd or 4th order depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming the quadrature rule has algebraic precision is of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, and the polynomial interpolation is of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, a straightforward analysis on local truncation error could be conducted. Approximation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 yields a truncation error of 
\begin_inset Formula $O((\inc t)^{m+2} )$
\end_inset

 expressed in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad3Err"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:Quad3Err}
    \begin{aligned}
        \uu^{n+1} - \uu^{n} = & \int_{t^n}^{t^{n+1}}{
        \R(t, \uu)\dd t}                              \\  = &
        {\inc t}^{n}
        \left[
            b_1\R(t^n, \uu(t^n))
            +
            b_2\R(t^{n+c_2}, \uu(t^{n+c_2}))
            +
            b_3\R(t^{n+1}, \uu(t^{n+1}))
            \right]
        \\ + &
        O((\inc t^{n})^{m+2} )
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

due to the precision degree of quadrature rule. Approximation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TR"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has a truncation error of 
\begin_inset Formula $O((\inc t)^{n+1})$
\end_inset

 expressed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TRErr"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \label{eq:TRErr}
        \uu(t^{n+c_2}) & =
        A^n_0(t^{n+c_2})\uu^{n - 1} +
        A^n_1(t^{n+c_2})\uu^{n} +
        A^n_2(t^{n+c_2})\uu^{n + 1}
        \\ & +
        \inc t^n D^n_0(t^{n+c_2})\R^{n - 1} +
        \inc t^n D^n_1(t^{n+c_2})\R^{n} +
        \inc t^n D^n_2(t^{n+c_2})\R^{n + 1}
        \\ & +
        O((\inc t^{n})^{n+1} )
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

as a result of polynomial degree. Substituting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TRErr"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into the 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 stage of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad3Err"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the truncation error of the entire scheme becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $O((\inc t)^{n+2}) + O((\inc t)^{m+2})$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \uu^{n+1} = & \uu^{n} + {\inc t}^{n}
        \left[
            b_1\R(t^n, \uu^n)
            +
            b_2\R(t^{n+c_2}, \uu^{n+c_2} + O((\inc t^{n})^{n+1} ))
            +
            b_3\R(t^{n+1}, \uu^{n+1})
            \right]
        \\ + &
        O((\inc t^{n})^{m+2} )               \\
        =           &
        \uu^{n} + {\inc t}^{n}
        \left[
            b_1\R(t^n, \uu^n)
            +
            b_2\R(t^{n+c_2}, \uu^{n+c_2})
            +
            b_3\R(t^{n+1}, \uu^{n+1})
            \right]
        \\ + &
        O((\inc t^{n})^{m+2}  + O((\inc t^{n})^{n+2} ))
    \end{aligned}
    \label{eq:fullLTE}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+1}, \uu^{n}$
\end_inset

 are step values assumed to be accurate here, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 is the approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

 stage value determined with temporal reconstruction. Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fullLTE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 assumes 
\begin_inset Formula $\R(t, \uu)$
\end_inset

 to be sufficiently regular and therefore does not change the order of error. Therefore, for smooth problems the order of accuracy of a DITR method is theoretically 
\begin_inset Formula $\min(m,n) + 1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

