\begin_inset Formula $c_2\in[1/2,1)$
\end_inset

 is a sufficient and necessary condition of DITR U2R2 being 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-stable given 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

. The limit at infinity 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \lim_{z\rightarrow\infty}R_{U2R2}(z) = \frac{1-c_2}{c_2}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

confirm that DITR U2R2 is unable to achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

-stability by adjusting 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DITR U2R2 (
\begin_inset Formula $c_2=1/2$
\end_inset

) or Lobatto IIIA method is symmetric, which is a preferable property when integrating reversible systems including orbital motion and particle systems. However, the symmetry in this ODE method could be considered harmful in CFD application. Most CFD systems of interest are physically dissipative, while for a symmetric method 
\begin_inset Formula $R(z) \rightarrow 1$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $z \rightarrow \infty$
\end_inset

, which means the method is more likely to preserve spurious modes arising from spacial discretization. Although DITR U2R2 cannot achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

-stability, using a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2 > 1/2$
\end_inset

 would still produce 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{z\rightarrow\infty}R(z)\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

, which would be a useful property in simulation of dissipative systems. With 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2 > 1/2$
\end_inset

, stiff modes could vanish faster over the time steps, while 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2 = 1/2$
\end_inset

 tends to preserve them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The DITR U2R1 Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Giving up one interpolation condition in DITR U2R2 forces the scheme to have 3rd order accuracy. The current paper removes 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 from U2R2, namely using 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n},\uu^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 for interpolation, which is able to produce an 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

-stable DITR scheme.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar with U2R2, DITR U2R1 has the interpolation written as: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \label{eq:TRU2R1}
        \uu^{n+c_2} & =
        a_{1,U2R1}\uu^{n} +
        a_{2,U2R1}\uu^{n + 1}
        \\ & +
        \inc t^n d_{2,U2R1}\R^{n + 1}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 being the numerical approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu(t^{n+c_2})$
\end_inset

 and the interpolation bases at 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

 node being: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        a_{1,U2R1} & = 1 - (2c_2 - {c_2}^2) \\
        a_{2,U2R1} & = 2c_2 - {c_2}^2       \\
        d_{2,U2R1} & = {c_2}^2 - {c_2}      \\
    \end{aligned}
    \label{eq:interpU2R1}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The temporal reconstruction equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TRU2R1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 combined with direct integration equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 forms the DITR U2R1 method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interpolation bases shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:interpU2R1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are quadratic. Therefore, the scheme yields 3rd order accuracy and the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

 does not affect the order of accuracy. Similar to U2R2, DITR U2R1's order of accuracy can be examined using standard procedures for Runge-Kutta methods
