\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The DITR U3R1 Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To exploit the information when multiple previous steps are available, using conditions from 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n-1}$
\end_inset

 would be preferable. The current paper chooses 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n-1},\uu^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 as U3R1's interpolation conditions, as other choices do not produce sufficient linear stability. The interpolation at 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

 node becomes: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \label{eq:TRU3R1}
        \uu^{n+c_2} & =
        a_{0,U3R1}\uu^{n} +
        a_{1,U3R1}\uu^{n} +
        a_{2,U3R1}\uu^{n + 1}
        \\ & +
        \inc t^n d_{2,U3R1}\R^{n + 1}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 being the numerical approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu(t^{n+c_2})$
\end_inset

 and the interpolation bases at 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2$
\end_inset

 node being: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        a_{0,U3R1} & = -\frac{c_{2}\,{\left(c_{2}-1\right)}^2}{\Theta\,{\left(\Theta+1\right)}^2}                                                            \\
        a_{1,U3R1} & = \frac{\left(\Theta+c_{2}\right)\,{\left(c_{2}-1\right)}^2}{\Theta}                                                                    \\
        a_{2,U3R1} & =  \frac{c_{2}\,\left(-\Theta^2\,c_{2}+2\,\Theta^2-\Theta\,{c_{2}}^2+3\,\Theta-2\,{c_{2}}^2+3\,c_{2}\right)}{{\left(\Theta+1\right)}^2} \\
        d_{2,U3R1} & =   \frac{c_{2}\,\left(\Theta+c_{2}\right)\,\left(c_{2}-1\right)}{\Theta+1}
    \end{aligned}
    \label{eq:interpU3R1}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta = \inc t^{n-1}/\inc t^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The temporal reconstruction equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TRU3R1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 combined with direct integration equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Quad3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 forms the DITR U2R1 method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method is 4th order when 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2=1/2$
\end_inset

, when both the interpolation and integration has precision of degree 3. For the special case of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2=1/2$
\end_inset

, simplified coefficients are given: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        a_{0,U3R1} & = -\frac{1}{8\,\Theta\,{\left(\Theta+1\right)}^2}                \\
        a_{1,U3R1} & = \frac{\Theta+\frac{1}{2}}{4\,\Theta}                           \\
        a_{2,U3R1} & =  \frac{6\,\Theta^2+11\,\Theta+4}{8\,{\left(\Theta+1\right)}^2} \\
        d_{2,U3R1} & = -\frac{\Theta+\frac{1}{2}}{4\,\left(\Theta+1\right)}
    \end{aligned}
    \label{eq:interpU3R1-S}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Linear stability is analyzed when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta =1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2 = 1/2$
\end_inset

. The solution to the test problem produces two solutions: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \left(
    \begin{matrix}
        R_{U3R1}^{(1)}(z) \\
        R_{U3R1}^{(2)}(z)
    \end{matrix}
    \right)=\left(\begin{array}{c} \frac{10\,z-\sqrt{-6\,z^3+129\,z^2+432\,z+576}+24}{6\,z^2-29\,z+48}\\ \frac{10\,z+\sqrt{-6\,z^3+129\,z^2+432\,z+576}+24}{6\,z^2-29\,z+48} \end{array}\right)
\end{equation}
\end_inset

It is obvious 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{U3R1}^{(1)}(z)\rightarrow 0, R_{U3R1}^{(2)}(z)\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $z\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

. When observed numerically, it is found both 
\begin_inset Formula $|R_{U3R1}^{(1)}(z)|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|R_{U3R1}^{(2)}(z)|$
\end_inset

 are less than 1 in the left half plane of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

. The current paper therefore believes 
