\begin_layout Standard
The DITR methods discussed in the current paper consist of two implicit equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DISum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TRSum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which are results of direct integration and temporal reconstruction respectively. There are two unknown vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+1},\uu^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 in the equations. In order to numerically conduct time marching with DITR, the equations need to be iteratively solved. The current section will discuss how to solve the equations arising from DITR methods when applied to spacial discretized flow problems, and describe a recommended solving approach in the end.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dual Time Stepping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "ssec:dualTime"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dual time stepping 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "jameson1991time,jameson2017evaluation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a standard procedure of solving nonlinear implicit time stepping equations in flow problems. The nonlinear equations are written in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \FF^*(\uu^*) = 0
    \label{eq:abstractImplicit}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

 represent one of the unknowns in DIRK, BDF or DITR methods. For example, for trapezoid rule (Crank-Nicolson method), equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:abstractImplicit"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 reads 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \label{eq:trapF}
    \FF(\uu^{n+1}) =
    -\frac{\uu^{n+1}-\uu^{n}}{\inc t^n} + \frac{\R^{n} + \R^{n+1}}{2}
    =0
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Generally, 
\begin_inset Formula $\FF^*$
\end_inset

 should be arranged so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\R(\uu^*)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\FF^*$
\end_inset

 has coefficient being 
\begin_inset Formula $O(1)$
\end_inset

 and positive, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

 has its coefficient being 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\inc t^{-1})$
\end_inset

 and negative. With the idea of dual time stepping, namely 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \frac{\dd\uu^{*}}{\dd \tau} = \FF^*(\uu^{*})
    \label{eq:exactDualTime}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

combined with a backward Euler method on the pseudo time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:abstractImplicit"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is solved with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \frac{\uu^{*,m+1} - \uu^{*,m}}{\inc \tau} = \FF^*(\uu^{*,m+1})
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m, m+1$
\end_inset

 are pseudo time steps. Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 has a dimension of time. Further linearizing would produce 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \left(\frac{\eye}{\inc\tau} -
    \partialderivative{\FF^*}{\uu^*}  \right)
    \inc\uu^{*,m} = \FF^*(\uu^{*,m})
    \label{eq:abstractNewton}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc\uu^{*,m} = \uu^{*,m+1} - \uu^{*,m}$
\end_inset

 is the increment of the iteration. The Jacobian of residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\partialderivative{\FF^*}{\uu^*}$
\end_inset

 is a non-trivial matrix, thus each update of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

 requires the solution of a sparse linear problem. When 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc\tau\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:abstractNewton"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 tends to reflect the exact evolution of dual time stepping equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:exactDualTime"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

. Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:abstractNewton"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 becomes the standard Newton-Raphson method when 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc\tau\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For DIRK type methods and linear multistep methods, at each step or stage, only one 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{*}$
\end_inset

 is unknown, thus equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:abstractNewton"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be applied directly. However, in fully implicit RK methods and the current DITR methods, more than one unknown 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{*}$
\end_inset

 are present at each stage. For example, in DITR methods, both 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+1},\uu^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 are present in both equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DISum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TRSum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

. Note that in equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DISum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TRSum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n+1},\R^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 are also dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+1},\uu^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

. Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 to be nonlinear, linear combinations of equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DISum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TRSum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are impossible to completely eliminate the dependence on one of 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+1},\uu^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

, and fully implicit RK methods share the same issue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the most obvious solutions to the multiple unknowns in DITR and fully implicit RK methods is to apply equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:abstractNewton"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to an enlarged system. The enlarged system concatenates different 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu$
\end_inset

 stages as one vector and uses the concatenated vector as 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:abstractNewton"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

. The residual function 
\begin_inset Formula $\FF^*$
\end_inset

 is therefore a concatenated vector of different stage equations' residual vectors. Therefore, for methods with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 unknown stages, the number of unknowns solved concurrently is 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 times of that in BDF or ESDIRK methods. Applied to DITR methods, there is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \uu^* = \begin{bmatrix}
        \uu^{n+c_2} \\
        \uu^{n+1}
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

and we denote 
\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\GG}{\mathcal{G}}
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \FF^* & =\begin{bmatrix}
                     \FF^{n+c_2} \\
                     \FF^{n+1}
                 \end{bmatrix} = \Pm\begin{bmatrix}
                                        \GG^{n+c_2} \\
                                        \GG^{n+1}
                                    \end{bmatrix} \\ & = \Pm\begin{bmatrix}
            \frac{a^n_0\uu^{n - 1} +
                a^n_1\uu^{n} +
                a^n_2\uu^{n + 1} - \uu^{n+c_2}}{\inc t^n}
            +
            d^n_1\R^{n} +
            d^n_2\R^{n + 1}
            \\
            \frac{\uu^{n} - \uu^{n+1}}{\inc t^n}  +
            b_1 \R^n +
            b_2 \R^{n+c_2} +
            b_3 \R^{n+1}
        \end{bmatrix}
        \label{eq:DITRFFDef}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pm$
\end_inset

 is a preconditioning matrix: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \Pm = \begin{bmatrix}
        \Pe_{11}\eye & \Pe_{12}\eye \\
        \Pe_{21}\eye & \Pe_{22}\eye \\
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\GG^{n+c_2},\GG^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 are the original residuals corresponding to temporal reconstruction 
