\begin_layout Subsection
The Nested Solving Approach of DITR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A characteristic of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TRSum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 only exists on the left side, namely the right side of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TRSum"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has only 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 as unknown. Consequently, by substitution, equivalent with the previous discussions causing equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fullLTE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 can be eliminated nonlinearly: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \uu^{n+1} & =                       \\
                  & \uu^{n} + \inc t\biggl[
        b_1 \R^n                            \\
                  & +
            b_2 \R(t^{n+c_2},a^n_0\uu^{n - 1} +
            a^n_1\uu^{n} +
            a^n_2\uu^{n + 1}
            +
            \inc t^n
            \left(
            d^n_1\R^{n} +
            d^n_2\R^{n + 1}
        \right))                            \\
                  & +
            b_3 \R(t^{n+1},\uu^{n+1})
            \biggr]
        \label{eq:nestedDITR}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

which we rewrite into the general form required in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "ssec:dualTime"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \FF(\uu^{n+1}) & = -\frac{\uu^{n+1} - \uu^{n}}{\inc t^n} \\
                       & +
        b_1 \R^n                                                 \\
                       & +
        b_2 \R\left(t^{n+c_2},a^n_0\uu^{n - 1} +
        a^n_1\uu^{n} +
        a^n_2\uu^{n + 1}
        +
        \inc t^n
        \left(
        d^n_1\R^{n} +
        d^n_2\R^{n + 1}
        \right)\right)                                           \\
                       & +
        b_3 \R(t^{n+1},\uu^{n+1}) = 0
        \label{eq:nestedDITR_F}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Next, using the linearized implicit backward Euler approximation, namely equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:abstractNewton"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, DITR methods can be solved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The huge advantage of this approach is that only one equation is solved, with only the next step value as unknown. This approach requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 to be nested in another 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 evaluation and is referred to as the nested solving approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nested solving approach exploits the local explicitness of DITR's formulation. The nested solving approach is similar, and sometimes equivalent with the solving approaches used in MIRK 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "cash1975classMIRKOrig,cash1977clasMIRK1,cash1982monoMIRK2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and NIRK 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "kulikov2006familyNIRKOrig,kulikov2009adaptive,kulikov2007asymptotic"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. However, previous research on MIRK and NIRK methods have not applied such solving approaches to flow problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numerical result indicate that with small 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc\tau$
\end_inset

 and relatively large 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc t$
\end_inset

, the nested solving approach usually fails to converge even in linear problems. Since dealing with large local CFL number with local pseudo time stepping is an essential ability of implicit time stepping methods, this divergent result denies the practicality of the nested solving approach.
\end_layout

