\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fourier Analysis for Pseudo Time: General Features
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To explain the failure of the nested solving approach in the presence of dual time stepping, Fourier analysis based on pseudo time is considered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To start the Fourier analysis, consider the linear convection problem solved on an infinitely large 1-D uniform grid. Suppose the 1-D linear convection problem reads 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \partialderivative{u}{t} = -a \partialderivative{u}{x}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

with positive convection speed 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

. Some difference scheme on uniform grid is used as spacial discretization: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \derivative{u_i}{t} = -\frac{a}{\inc x} \sum_{j\in S_i}u_j\alpha_j
    \label{eq:fd}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_j$
\end_inset

 is the coefficients for finite difference approximation and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_i$
\end_inset

 is the stencil set. As the problem is linear, a simple wave solution 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    u = A(t)\exp(\imagUnit \frac{\kappa}{\inc x} x)
\end{equation}
\end_inset

can be substituted in and produces a relation of 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \frac{\dd A(t)}{\dd t} = -\imagUnit a\frac{\kappa'}{\inc x}  A(t)
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa'$
\end_inset

 is the modified non-dimensional wave number, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\imagUnit$
\end_inset

 is the imaginary unit. For a finite difference scheme in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fd"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa'$
\end_inset

 can be found as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \kappa' = \frac{1}{\imagUnit} \sum_{j\in S_i}\exp(\imagUnit (j-i)\kappa)\alpha_j
\end{equation}
\end_inset

The modified wave number 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa'$
\end_inset

 is commonly used to evaluate the performance of spacial discretization schemes. A stable discretization would require 
\begin_inset Formula $\imag(\kappa) \leq 0$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)$
\end_inset

 does not exponentially increase in magnitude.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, the classic linear analysis on dissipation and dispersion is extended to dual time stepping. The dual time stepping equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:exactDualTime"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be considered an evolution of the solution. Thus, for the linear convection problem, a simple wave pseudo time solution 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    u^*(\tau,x) = A^*(\tau)\exp(\imagUnit \frac{\kappa}{\inc x} x)
    \label{eq:simpleWaveTestTau}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 represent a certain unknown stage or step value. Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \frac{\dd A^*(\tau)}{\dd \tau} = -\imagUnit a\frac{\kappa^*}{\inc x}  A^*(\tau) + C^*
    \label{eq:kappaSDefTau}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^*$
\end_inset

 represents the modified wave number for pseudo time. The 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 term in the above equation is a constant coefficient arising from the transient terms in the time stepping method. In order to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^*$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\FF^*$
\end_inset

 need to be specified. If we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\FF^*$
\end_inset

 is in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \FF^*(\uu^*) = \mathbf{C} - \frac{\mathcal{A}}{\inc t} \uu^* + \mathcal{B}\R(t^*, \uu^*)
    \label{eq:canonicalFF}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is the part of vectors irrelevant with 
\begin_inset Formula $\uu^*$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 are positive coefficients. Evidently ESDIRK, BDF and trapezoid rule (as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:trapF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can satisfy this form. Using the finite difference 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fd"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 is determined, and it is shown that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\FF$
\end_inset

 having equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:canonicalFF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

's form, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^*$
\end_inset

 is found to be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \kappa^* = -\imagUnit\frac{\mathcal{A}}{\CFLt} +
    \frac{\mathcal{B}}{\imagUnit} \sum_{j\in S_i}\exp(\imagUnit (j-i)\kappa)\alpha_j
    =-\imagUnit\frac{\mathcal{A}}{\CFLt} + \mathcal{B}\kappa'
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\CFLt = \frac{a\inc t }{\inc x}$
\end_inset

 is the physical CFL number. When the finite difference is stable, 
\begin_inset Formula $\imag (\kappa') \leq 0$
\end_inset

, and consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $\imag (\kappa^*) < 0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarize, for stage residual function 
\begin_inset Formula $\FF^*$
\end_inset

 in the form of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:canonicalFF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, it is guaranteed 
\begin_inset Formula $\imag (\kappa^*) < 0$
\end_inset

, and the pseudo time evolution is stable in the sense of a continuous 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result offers an aspect of reason behind using dual time stepping, that it is automatically stable when applied to common ODE methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fourier Analysis for Pseudo Time: on Nested Solving Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Back to the current section's subject, DITR's nested solving approach, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\FF$
\end_inset

 is defined with equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:nestedDITR_F"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, does not satisfy the form of equation 
