\begin_layout Standard
The preconditioning parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, as discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sssec:SDSFourier"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sssec:GSStability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, affects convergence properties of the stage-decoupled solving strategy. When 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc \tau\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, as discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sssec:SDSFourier"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\max(\real(\mu^*_1),\real(\mu^*_2))$
\end_inset

 represents the linear growth rate of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 evolution. When the DITR method parameters are settled, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^*_1=\mu^*_1(\beta, \mu')$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^*_2=\mu^*_2(\beta, \mu')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{GS}=G_{GS}(\beta, z)$
\end_inset

. When 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc \tau\rightarrow+\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|G_{GS}|$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sssec:GSStability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 represents the magnifying factor in the Gauss-Seidel updating. Similar to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-stability of ODE integrators, the relations: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \max(\real(\mu^*_1),\real(\mu^*_2)) \leq 0,\ \forall \real(\mu') \leq 0
\end{equation}
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    |G_{GS}| \leq 1,\ \forall \real(z) \leq 0
\end{equation}
\end_inset

are referred to as the 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\tau,0)-$
\end_inset

stability and 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\tau,\infty)-$
\end_inset

stability of the stage-decoupled solving approach. The current paper hopes to utilize both extremes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc\tau$
\end_inset

 to narrow down the choice of an optimized 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is restrained to be no greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $O(1)$
\end_inset

 to make the preconditioning non-singular. Meanwhile, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\leq 0$
\end_inset

 leads to a negative coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\FF^{n+c_2}$
\end_inset

 according to 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
eeqref{
\end_layout

\end_inset

eq:DITRFFDef
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which almost guarantees the loss of stability. Therefore, empirically, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in[0,2]$
\end_inset

 is to be the numerical scanning interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, given a certain 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 value and a certain DITR method, the stability indicators 
\begin_inset Formula $\max(\real(\mu^*_1),\real(\mu^*_2))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|G_{GS}|$
\end_inset

 can be calculated as functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 respectively. To check on the 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\tau,0)-$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\tau,\infty)-$
\end_inset

stability of this certain 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 choice, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 are numerically sampled in the left half complex plane. The samples include 
\begin_inset Formula $101\times101$
\end_inset

 uniform points in 
\begin_inset Formula $[-10,0]\times[0,10]$
\end_inset

. Furthermore, radially distributed points with 101 argument samples in 
\begin_inset Formula $[\pi/2,\pi]$
\end_inset

 and 10 exponentially distributed radius samples in 
\begin_inset Formula $[10^1, 10^{10}]$
\end_inset

 are included. Note that the sample points are all above the real axis, because the distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\max(\real(\mu^*_1),\real(\mu^*_2))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|G_{GS}|$
\end_inset

 are symmetric about the real axis with the DITR coefficients being real. The numeric sample points form the sample sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mu'_i\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{z_i\}$
\end_inset

. Then, the numeric maximums are calculated: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \begin{aligned}
        \mu^*_{M}(\beta) & = \max_{i}\{\max(\real(\mu^*_1(\beta,\mu'_i)),\real(\mu^*_2(\beta,\mu'_i)))\} \\
        G_{GS,M}(\beta)  & = \max_{i}\{|G_{GS}(\beta,z_i)|\}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

if for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\beta_0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^*_{M}(\beta_0) \leq 0,G_{GS,M}(\beta_0) \leq 1$
\end_inset

, it is known for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\beta_0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\tau,0)-$
\end_inset

stability and 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\tau,\infty)-$
\end_inset

stability are achieved.
\end_layout

