\begin_layout Standard
The isentropic vortex problem is a classic accuracy testing problem for Euler equations. The settings can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "hu1999weighted_WENO"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. The free-stream flow is 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho,u,v,p)=(1,1,1,1)$
\end_inset

, and a perturbation at initial time: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \left\{
    \begin{array}[2]{ll}
        (\delta u, \delta v) & = \frac{\epsilon}{2\pi}\exp(\frac{1-[(x-x_c)^2+(y-y_c)^2]}{2})(-y+y_c,x-x_c) \\
        \delta T             & = - \frac{(\gamma-1)\epsilon^2}{8\gamma\pi^2}\exp(1-[(x-x_c)^2+(y-y_c)^2])   \\
        \delta S             & = 0                                                                          \\
    \end{array}
    \right.
\end{equation}
\end_inset

with ideal gas setting of 
\begin_inset Formula $T = p/\rho, S= p/\rho^\gamma, \gamma =1.4$
\end_inset

. Initial vortex center is chosen 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_c,y_c)=(5,5)$
\end_inset

, and vortex strength is 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon = 5$
\end_inset

. The analytic solution to the isentropic vortex problem is a translation of initial field with speed 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

. The computational domain is 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,10]\times[0,10]$
\end_inset

, using periodic boundary conditions.
\end_layout

