\begin_layout Standard
The double Mach reflection problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "woodward1984dmr"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is tested to compare the resolution capabilities of different time marching schemes. The double Mach reflection computes inviscid ideal gas in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,4]\times[0,1]$
\end_inset

, initialized by a Ma 10 moving shock located at 
\begin_inset Formula $x = 1/6 + \cot(60^\circ) y$
\end_inset

. The boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0, x\in[1/6,4]$
\end_inset

 is inviscid wall, and all other boundaries conforms with the Ma 10 moving shock. Details about the initial and boundary settings may be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "woodward1984dmr"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. The compact FV scheme is additionally equipped with an accuracy preserving CWBAP limiter 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "wu2023cwbap"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which grants the ability to capture spacial discontinuities. To handle strong discontinuities, the local Lax-Friedrichs flux is used here. The computations are conducted on a uniform quadrilateral mesh with mesh size 
\begin_inset Formula $h=1/480$
\end_inset

. Physical time step is set to a relatively large 
\begin_inset Formula $\inc t= 2\times10^{-4}$
\end_inset

, and the solutions at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0.25$
\end_inset

 are compared.
\end_layout

